fields.title: Things to do for a monkey in Hartlepool
fields.content: In general, a drop-dead story about the Soviet Union. After all, no one will argue with the fact that while there in the decaying bourgeois West everyone was tearing each other to pieces, in the country the not-yet-to-the-end-but-just-a-little-more-will-be-victor -Communism reigned stability and equality. Everyone in front of everyone. And even the crimes that were committed by various irresponsible individuals who fell under the influence of Western countries were immediately revealed, as they say, without delay. What can we say - the police worked for us as they should. The detection rate in the Soviet Union was at a level close to ideal. Not 100%, of course, but 90% for sure. Where are all the capitalist policemen who only basked in the rays of their patrons from the rich strata and who beat up ordinary workers at rallies. Our people's police, together with the vigilantes, cracked things like nuts. Yes, there were people in the police in those days. Real investigators and detectives. Any case could be solved. And here is the story of perhaps the best detective of the Soviet Union. Zhavnerovich Michal Kuzmich.

fields.title: Five strange facts.
fields.content: In short, if I understand correctly, this is the very point where all the great samurai hemorrhage began. Well, remember when a Japanese blow immediately causes a fountain of blood to flow from a sword strike. And here's the movie Sanjuro. Naturally, this is Kurosawa. And the point of this whole fact is that this was a complete accident. A much more natural reaction of the wound should have occurred - simply bleeding. But the bag with the liquid accidentally tore and the contents rushed out all at once. And there was quite a lot - the volume was calculated for several takes. And it resulted in one. But everyone on the set thought it was cool. So much so that they left the take, and the trope went into films and among the people.

fields.title: How Room 8 conquered first the school, and then California
fields.content:
Room 8 received tens of thousands of fan letters during his lifetime. A documentary was made about him, a book and a song were written. Articles about him were published in Time, Look and many other publications. His fingerprints are immortalized in cement next to the school for which he became famous. And the obituary in the Los Angeles Times took up three columns and a photomore than most people. Well, not bad for a person, you might think, even with such a strange nickname (we bet this is a rapper). Yes, but he's not human. It's a cat. And all his achievements... in the spirit of a cat and the bonds of cuteness, independence and indifference. In general, Monday today will be marked by cuteness and fluffiness.

fields.title: Kayfebe and the most famous jester in the WWF
fields.content: Now let's talk about sports. Ill say right away that Im not a fan of this area of human activity. I generally consider professional work in this area to be of little use to society. But now I remember how in the early 90s, with the advent of cable TV in our outback, I once came across wrestling. And... no, I wont say that I got involved and became a fan for the rest of my life. Not at all. But in the fragile childs mind, the very idea of healthy, brutal men attacking each other in the ring, violating all kinds of laws and ignoring the common sense of any fight, had the effect of an exploding bomb. Seriously? No rules? They actually grabbed chairs, pushed the referee away, rushed at the spectators and jumped like wild kangaroos on the opponent. From scraps of information and omissions, I realized that this was part of something larger. The nasal translator, confused by names and titles, mumbled that someone had offended someone there, and now let revenge be taken! He threw around names and details of history that neither the translator himself nor I understood. It was as if you opened a book series somewhere on the fifth book. No, like I said, I never became a fan, but I still remember the dude called The Undertaker. And heated arguments not only between children, but also adults come to mind - is it really true that they really show such a fight? Have they gone completely crazy there in the USA? I always thought that this was a production in its purest form. Even the blood on their faces didnt bother me (later it turned out that the wounds were inflicted with special small blades during the battle). Well, yes, as I got older, I realized that this turns out to be not just a show or an extreme theatrical performance, but a whole huge universe with direction and plot, spreading

fields.title: When there is absolutely nothing to do
fields.content: So, suddenly for yourself, you found out that football battles are not for you. Too poppy. DoTA Championship? A lot of running and flickering. Well, yes, I agree with this. What else is left there? Poker!! Not bad, but do you want something exotic? How about snooker? Even more unusual? Strange. And so I present to you: behold! FMWC (Financial Modeling World Cup). I'm sure there are at least a few people here who launch Excel every day to build some interesting model or solve a tricky problem! And they probably know about this cup (or learned about it from this story). I dedicate this story to everyone else. So, the championship itself is not particularly promoted yet (although it is sponsored, of course, by Microsoft and fucking you wont guess it, Eve Online). The prize fund is around 20 thousand dollars (the winner will receive half), and the finale on YouTube only received about half a million views. But at the same time, a) ESPN is already broadcasting it, b) they have their own merch, c) last years final was held in Las Vegas, d) the leaders were clearly identified among the participants and a world ranking was compiled. In short, this is a completely new direction in sports disciplines. And what is it about?
